<https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/library/RT3CM832>
  a schema:ScholarlyArticle ;
  schema:name "Reconsidering the Underground Railroad: Slavery and Racialization in the Making of the Canadian State" ;
  schema:url <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/library/?item=RT3CM832> ;
  dcterms:isPartOf <https://medjat.irokosociety.org/id/collection/medjat-library> ;
  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:RT3CM832" ;
  schema:description "The Underground Railroad is commonly understood as a defining moment in the ideology of the Canadian state regarding the legacy of racism and anti-racism. This paper attempts to recast the narrative of the Underground Railroad through the lens of an anti-imperialist, anti-racist political economy, departing from the view of Canada’s anti-racist rescue of fugitive slaves from racist America. The Underground Railroad was in fact the product primarily of the struggle for self-emancipation of American black slaves. The central place of these actors as agents of their own freedom struggle needs to be recognized and restored, taken as a theoretical and historical starting point in explaining the pre-history of Confederation. The British North American colonies served as a safe space for fugitive slaves as a result of realpolitik; racism and a culture of hegemonic whiteness were endemic to the early origins of the Canadian state. This analysis is placed in the context of current and historical discussions of anti-racism and anti-imperialism." ;
  schema:author "Abigail B. Bakan" ;
  schema:datePublished "2008" ;
  schema:publisher "Socialist studies" ;
  schema:sameAs <https://doi.org/10.18740/s4c59d> ;
  dcterms:identifier "doi:10.18740/s4c59d" ;
  dcterms:subject "Australian History and Society", "Canadian Identity and History", "Race, History, and American Society" .
